A new API to get the Most Significant Bit of a BigInteger, a more efficient way to compute bit length than Log (**floating point** base 2, for some reason there is no Log2 method even though it will enable faster computation, but that's another story).

[Java docs for equivalent method](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigInteger.html#bitLength())

Implementation implies zero impact on existing code, maintenance cost is expected to be low.

# Current story
```cs
private static int SlowBitLength(BigInteger integer)
{
    return (int) Math.Ceiling(BigInteger.Log(BigInteger.Abs(integer) + 1, 2.0));
}

private static int VerySlowBitLength(BigInteger integer)
{
    if (integer.IsZero)
        return 0;

    var bitLength = 0;

    do
    {
        bitLength++;
        integer /= 2;
    } while (!integer.IsZero);

    return bitLength;
}
```

# Proposed API
```cs
public readonly struct BigInteger : <...>
{
	<...>
    public int BitLength { get; }
	<...>
}
```

# Proposed implementation
```cs
public int BitLength
{
    get
    {
        uint[] xd;
        int xl;
        
        var value = this;
        GetPartsForBitManipulation(ref value, out xd, out xl);

        var h = xd[xl - 1];
        var c = NumericsHelpers.CbitHighZero(h);
        var b = xl * 32 - c;

        return b;
    }
}
```

Based on Log code:
<https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/191ad0b5d52172366436322bf9d553dc770d23b1/src/System.Runtime.Numerics/src/System/Numerics/BigInteger.cs#L795-L820>

